## Summary

This PR adds end-to-end support for function values (closures) in the Move Prover, enabling verification of higher-order functions using behavioral predicates.

At this point most of the desired verification scenarios work:

- We can specify and verify higher-order functions standalone (like contains, index_of, reduce) 
- Those HO functions are verified at caller site for preconditions on functional parameters -- e.g. `requires !aborts_of<f>(x)` demands that any passed `f` function does not abort on the value `x`.
- HO functions can be made opaque, and the caller side is handled via specs only, making code with them verify faster

For some [examples see here](https://github.com/aptos-labs/aptos-core/blob/wrwg/fval4/third_party/move/move-prover/tests/sources/functional/closures/behavioral_predicates_examples.move).

What is not working yet:

- No inference of specs from code -- want to say `index_of(v, |e| { e > 0 } spec { .. })` without the need for spec block of the lambda. Work in progress in child PR for weakest precondition based spec inference
- No support of global state and the modifies_of<f> primitive 


### Behavioral Predicates

Behavioral predicates (`requires_of`, `aborts_of`, `ensures_of`) allow specifying how a function parameter's behavior affects the enclosing function's spec:

```move
fun apply(f: |u64| u64, x: u64): u64 { f(x) }
spec apply {
    requires requires_of<f>(x);
    aborts_if aborts_of<f>(x);
    ensures ensures_of<f>(x, result);
    // alt notation: 
    // ensures result == result_of<f>(x);
}

// Caller with concrete closure - verifies that result == 6
fun test(): u64 {
    apply(|y| y + 5 spec { ensures result == y + 5; }, 1)
}
spec test { ensures result == 6; }
```

For every predicate `ensures_of<f>(x, y)` there is also a function `result_of<f>(x)` defined as `choose y where ensures<f>(x, y)`. The functional notation is often more convenient and reflects that `ensures_of` is in fact
